======================================================================
  PART 10: SYNTHESIS — 5 AS DISCRIMINANT MODULUS
======================================================================

THEOREM (informal): 5 is the discriminant modulus of the
tournament recurrence tower.

Evidence:
1. The second-order recurrence f(n) = f(n-1) + x·f(n-2)
   has discriminant Δ = 1+4x.
   At x=1: Δ = 5 (the Fibonacci case)
   At x=2: Δ = 9 = 3² (the Jacobsthal/tournament case)

2. The transition from irrational (√5) to rational (3)
   discriminant happens at x = 1 → x = 2.
   This is the SAME transition as Fibonacci → Jacobsthal.

3. The integer-discriminant points are x = k(k-1):
   x=0: Δ=1, x=2: Δ=9, x=6: Δ=25, x=12: Δ=49, ...
   The discriminants are: 1², 3², 5², 7², 9², 11², ...
   AND 5 APPEARS IN THIS SEQUENCE (at x=6, Δ=25=5²).

4. The Q(√5) field connects:
   x=1 (Fibonacci, Δ=5) ↔ x=11 (Δ=45=9·5) ↔ x=31 (Δ=125=25·5)
   These x-values are (5m²-1)/4 for m=1,3,5,...

5. At x=11: roots = (1±3√5)/2 = {3φ-1, 2-3φ}
   So x=11 roots are EXACTLY 3× Fibonacci roots, shifted by -1.
   The 'decimal pair' (10,11) connects to the golden ratio!

6. The J₆ sequence (x=6 level, denominator 5) generates 7:
   J₆(3) = (3³-(-2)³)/5 = (27+8)/5 = 35/5 = 7
   So 5 GENERATES the (7,8) transition threshold.

CONCLUSION: 5 is the algebraic number that makes the
Fibonacci→Jacobsthal transition WORK. It is the discriminant
of the base case (x=1), and through Q(√5) it threads through
the entire hierarchy: 1→5→11→31→... All levels where the
golden ratio echoes in the tournament structure.

Done.
